{
  "text": "There are n persons, each of whom needs to be identified as a member of one of m groups. Let N ≡ {1 n} be the set of persons and let G ≡ {1 m} be the set of groups. We assume, unless noted otherwise, that n ≥ 2 and m ≥ 3. Each person i ∈ N has an opinion on who she believes are the members of each of these groups. The opinion is represented by a list P i ≡ (P ij ) j∈N ∈ G N , where for all j ∈ N 5 [CITATION_1] study the extended model without the single-membership property and the extended consent rules. The role of the single-membership property is discussed more explicitly there. See also footnote 11. 6 Meet separability requires the equivalence of (i) the conjunction of the two decisions for group \"J\" and group \"K\", and (ii) the decision for group \"J and K\". Join separability requires the equivalence of (i) the disjunction of the two decisions for group \"J\" and group \"K\", and (ii) the decision for group \"J or K\". 7 It requires, for instance, that the decision on group \"J and K\" be independent of the opinions on group \"J\" or the opinions on group \"K\", which are quite relevant. 8 See Theorem 1 in [CITATION_2] .",
